2 - Answers to the questions¶

A - Have wildfires become more or less frequent over time?¶

In order to find frequency of fires, daily, monthly and yearly counts will be extracted from the time-series data. For the trend and seasonality detection, Meta's fbprophet module will be used.

EDA and Feature Engineering¶

In [46]:
def prophet_model(time_series_df,
                  growth = "linear",
                  interval_width=0.95, 
                  changepoint_range=0.8, 
                  changepoint_prior_scale=1, 
                  seasonality_mode='multiplicative', 
                  n_changepoints=50,
                  periods=36, 
                  freq='M', 
                  holidays_prior_scale = 0.0,
                  yearly_seasonality = True,
                  daily_seasonality = False,
                  weekly_seasonality = False):
    """This function is used to implement Fbprophet on the given time-series data. The inputs are set with
    their default values. Parameter descriptions are in the following source: 
    https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/prophet/prophet.pdf"""
    # Convert column names as proposed
    df_prophet = time_series_df.reset_index()
    df_prophet.columns = ["ds","y"]
    # Fit the model with the given parameters.
    m = Prophet(growth=growth,interval_width=interval_width, changepoint_range=changepoint_range, changepoint_prior_scale=changepoint_prior_scale, seasonality_mode=seasonality_mode, n_changepoints=n_changepoints,yearly_seasonality=yearly_seasonality,daily_seasonality=daily_seasonality,weekly_seasonality=weekly_seasonality)
    m.fit(df_prophet)
    # Make future data frame to retrieve trends.
    future = m.make_future_dataframe(periods=periods, freq=freq)
    forecast = m.predict(future)
    return m,forecast

By looking the at the trends, the question can be answered yearly and overal.¶

  • In the yearly averages, spring and summer months have higest fire rates.(March, April, July, August)
  • Finally, in the overal trend, we can conclude that up to 2011 the fires have become more frequent. And after 2011, the fires have become less frequent.

In order to create an automated answer we need to extract the trend change points and calculate slopes of the trends.

In [48]:
# Obtain trend change points.
fig = m.plot(forecast)
a = add_changepoints_to_plot(fig.gca(), m, forecast)
In [49]:
# Divide the dataset into portions lower and upper of the change point.
trend = forecast[["ds","trend"]]
lower_portion = trend[(trend["ds"]<m.changepoints.to_list()[0])]
upper_portion = trend[(trend["ds"]>m.changepoints.to_list()[0])]

# Calculate slopes with using linear Regression.
reg_lower = linear_model.LinearRegression()
reg_upper = linear_model.LinearRegression()

reg_lower.fit(pd.to_datetime(lower_portion['ds']).map(dt.datetime.toordinal).values.reshape(-1, 1), lower_portion['trend'].values)
reg_upper.fit(pd.to_datetime(upper_portion['ds']).map(dt.datetime.toordinal).values.reshape(-1, 1), upper_portion['trend'].values)

print(f"Slope before changepoint({m.changepoints.to_list()[0]}): {reg_lower.coef_}")
print(f"Slope before changepoint({m.changepoints.to_list()[0]}): {reg_upper.coef_}")

Slope before changepoint(2011-03-13 00:00:00): [0.00744251]
Slope before changepoint(2011-03-13 00:00:00): [-0.04283992]

We can use the above calculations to develop automation for this question. If the slope before changepoint is positive that means the fires have become more frequent up to the changepoint, and vise-wersa is also true.

B - What counties are the most and least fire-prone?¶

Fire Durations, Fire Sizes and Fire Counts can give idea about the proneness of the counties. Fire Counts are calculated in the previous question. Fire sizes are already exist in the dataset. Fire duration will be calculated. In order to find a final alignment between counties these features will be reduced to one with using Princaipal Component Analysis.

EDA and Feature Engineering¶

# Convert Julian time.

df_duration["combined_date_dis"] = pd.to_datetime(df_duration["combined_date_dis"], format = "%Y%j")

df_duration["combined_date_dis"] = pd.to_datetime(df_duration["combined_date_dis"])
df_duration["combined_date_con"] = df_duration["FIRE_YEAR"]*1000 + df_duration["CONT_DOY"]
df_duration["combined_date_con"] = pd.to_datetime(df_duration["combined_date_con"], format = "%Y%j",errors="ignore")
df_duration["combined_date_con"] = df_duration.combined_date_con.astype(str) + " " + df_duration.CONT_TIME.str[:2] + ":" + df_duration.CONT_TIME.str[2:]
df_duration["combined_date_con"] = pd.to_datetime(df_duration["combined_date_con"],errors="coerce")
df_duration["duration"] = None
# Calculate Fire Durations from the difference of Discovery and Control times.
df_duration.loc[df_duration['combined_date_con'].notna(), 'duration'] = (df_duration["combined_date_con"] - df_duration["combined_date_dis"]).dt.seconds/60
df_duration = df_duration.set_index("combined_date_dis")
df_duration["duration"] = df_duration.duration.astype(float)

From the above graphs, the following results are obtained:

  • In terms of Duration, the counties Coconino(AZ) and Idaho(ID) have the highest total duration of fire.
  • In terms of Fire Size, the counties Elco(NV) has the highest total size of fire.
  • In terms of Fire Counts, Coconino(AZ) and Suffolk(NY) have the highest total duration of fire.

A resultant final metric that is a kind of linear combinations of this three features can be obtained with using Principal Component Analysis(PCA). PCA basically implement Eigenvalues Decomposition on the covariance matrix of the input data and extracts the linear combinations of the input features and sorts these components based on their variences. The principal component that has the highest varience, also has the highest information representation of the dataset. So, this component can be used as a common metric of pronenes for the counties.

In [56]:
# Combine the metrics into the same data frame.

df_fire_duration = df_duration.groupby(["State_County"]).sum().reset_index()[["State_County","duration"]]
df_proneness = df_fire_counts.merge(df_fire_size,on="State_County",how="inner").merge(df_fire_duration,on="State_County",how="inner")

# Implement PCA and calculate the variences of the principal components.
pca = PCA()
pca.fit_transform(scaled)
pca_variance = pca.explained_variance_

# Visualize the variance ratio of all principle components.
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.bar(range(3), pca_variance, alpha=0.5, align='center', label='individual variance')
plt.legend()
plt.ylabel('Variance Ratio')
plt.xlabel('Principal components')
plt.show()

The first principal component's varience is significantly higher than the rest, so the first one has the highest information related with the dataset and can be used as proneness metric.

C - Given the size, location and date, can you predict the cause of a fire wildfire?

In order to develop a model that can predict the cause of fire, all related features needs to be extracted from the dataset. These features are the days of the week, month of the year and fire duration.

EDA and Feature Engineering¶

The data is so unbalanced. Some over or under sampling techniques are required to balance the data. Also the rate of the category(Debris Burning) that has the highest counts is %23. So, after the completing the modeling, the accuracy rate of the model must be at least %23.

Before implementing the data to the models, the nominal categorical values must be converted to One-Hot-Encoded format. In the dataset, the State and the County features have nominal categories. Other categorical values are ordinal. Because of the memory that is not capable of handling One-Hot-Encoded(OHE) 1900 features of County(FIPS_NAME) and STATE, OHE is not implemented on these features. In order to lower the memory consumption Feature Selection techniques like SelectKBest or Recursive Feature Elimination or sampling techniques to lower the data amount are tested. However the results were even worse. The tests result showed that inplementing only label encoding(not OHE) on STATE and COUNTY features gave higher performance for this case. So, in this model implementation, only label encoding will be used on STATE and COUNTY.

df_model = df_model[["FIRE_YEAR","STAT_CAUSE_DESCR","FIRE_SIZE","LATITUDE","LONGITUDE","FIPS_NAME","STATE","duration","week_day","month"]]

# Implement Label Encoding for the State and Fips Name.
fips_le = LabelEncoder()
fips_labels = fips_le.fit_transform(df_model.FIPS_NAME)
df_model["FIPS_NAME"] = fips_labels

state_le = LabelEncoder()
state_labels = state_le.fit_transform(df_model.STATE)
df_model["STATE"] = state_labels

# Instead of using STAT_CAUSE_CODE as label, implement LE for STAT_CAUSE_DESCR because STAT_CAUSE_CODE starts from 1.
le = LabelEncoder()
df_model["STAT_CAUSE_DESCR"] = le.fit_transform(df_model['STAT_CAUSE_DESCR'])
df_model["STAT_CAUSE_DESCR"] = df_model.STAT_CAUSE_DESCR.astype(int)

The fire duration feature is calculated with CONT_TIME and DISCOVERY_TIME. The CONT_TIME feature has approximately 800k nan values. So, if the duration feature was included in the training data, a large portion of data was set as na. Models like Random Forest are unable to handle nan values. For this reason, nan's are droped once the data was implemented on Random Forest and other models. Since, Xgboost is capable of handling nan values, both with and without na values, the data is implemented on Xgboost. Resultant accuracies are as follows:

  • Random forest 0.62
  • Xgboost 0.60 without na (890796 rows)
  • Xgboost 0.56 with na (1313835 rows)

Low accuracy on Xgboost even with higher amount of data shows that there is an overfitting on the model.

The following classification models are implemented and the resultant accuracies are recorded:

  • Random Forest : 0.62
  • Xgboost Classifier : 0.60
  • DecisionTreeClassifier : 0.50
  • KNeighbors Classifier : 0.47
  • AdaBoostClassifier : 0.47
  • Gradient Boosting Classifier : 0.46
  • Ridge Classifier : 0.40
  • Logistic Regression CV : 0.40
  • Naive Bayes : 0.35
  • Logistic Regression : 0.35
  • Linear SVC : 0.25
  • SGD Classifier : 0.17

This results show that the decision tree classifier is not as good as the ensemble methods such as Random Forest and Xgboost classifiers. These ensemble methods combine several decision trees and make a poll among these weak learners to form a strong learner.

Since the the data is hugh and there are several features, the simplistic models like Logistic Regression, Linear SVC, SGD and Naive Bayes classifiers falls in the underfitting area and performed worse than more complex models like Decision Trees and ensemble models. Another conclusion from these result is that, the linear models are far worse than the ensemble methods. The Normalization and Standartization techniques(effective on linear models) are applied on the data and tested again. Although, especially linear models performance increased, their performances were still far less than the ensemble models.

Comparison of the F1 Scores of each label shows that Random Forest performs worse on the following labels.

Children, Miscellaneous, Powerline, Railroad, Smoking

Since the number of labels in the dependent variable is high, it is unlikely to obtain higher accuracy rates. In order to decrease the number of the labels, we can ramove Miscellaneous and Missing/Undefined. These causes can be set in case of fires that have variety of values in their features, which may consider as noise for our model. If the dataset is noisy, then the complex models can fit with noise. And this situation results with low accuracy rates.

Removing Miscellaneous and Missing/Undefined labels increased our accuracy to 0.66. Grouping the labels, or even reduce the number of labels to one(transforming the problem into a binary classification problem.) may increase the accuracy to higher rates.

As discussed in the EDA section, the classes are highly inbalanced. To balance the data with SMOTE, can be a good option to increase the accuracy. After the following implemetation, it is shown in the graph that all labels become in the same rates.(Since this is an oversampling the data increased by 4 times.) For the computational costs constraints, after oversampling, an undersampling can be done. But this is not required for this case.
